A New Science
This summer, an unusual conference took place in Paris. There, scientists gathered to consider the necessity of a new science that could be as revolutionary as Einstein's insights a hundred years ago.
The majority of scientists believe that the fundamental questions of the sciences have been answered.
With regard to the great challenges, it is considered that there is little left to discover.
The remaining questions can be divided into three groups: First, the great unsolved mysteries of science (such as the unification of gravity and electricity in a theory), whose exploration requires enormous investments and the infrastructure of the First World. Second, data collection, which refers to work related to archaeological excavations and biological/genetic studies, and third, problems whose solution must be based on scientific foundations, such as the fight against AIDS or global warming.
Darüber hinaus ist man vielerorts der Meinung, dass der einzig schwierige Teil der Arbeit darin bestünde, bereits bekannte Naturgesetze mit Hilfe neuer Technologien zum Wohle der Menschheit zu nutzen.
Who could deny that?
The models of today work, after all.
A growing group of scientists, however, points to phenomena that are not well explained by today's theories.
These problems occur more and more frequently, but are also skillfully circumvented, because there is simply no science that would explain these problems.
This missing science would describe processes and the emergence of entire systems.
In the individual scientific disciplines, knowledge is somewhat well established.
Physics, at least the part of it with which we common mortals are confronted, is well researched.
Chemistry and biochemistry also stand on solid foundations – although there are still a few things in our body that we do not yet understand, it can be assumed that the basic mechanisms of interaction between cells and molecules are known.
There are also the new social sciences, which focus on people and societies.
In each of these areas – physics, biochemistry, and social sciences – the theories are well-established and are largely beyond dispute.
Each discipline has its own language and its own mechanisms.
Scientists are experts in more than one field in the rarest of cases, because these worlds and languages are so different.
This means that we cannot find answers to complex questions that require the involvement of multiple disciplines.
For example, one might think of the brain.
This complex organ consists of molecules, whose interaction is based on the principles of physics. The information conveyed in this process is transmitted according to the laws of electricity.
Additionally, there is a system of specialized cells that communicate through the exchange of chemical substances and also transmit information in this way.
When two brains interact, a new level is added: Here, the exchange of information occurs through language, symbols, and concepts.
On each level, it is about the exchange of information, and there are appropriate theories that explain the processes on each individual level.
Information is also exchanged between the individual levels, but there is no science that could even begin to explain this information exchange.
To compensate for this deficiency, some scientists have tried to redefine the instrumental framework for explaining processes within a level, in order to then apply it on another level.
These attempts then lead to something like a "language" at the cellular level and "energy" behind organized societies.
Sometimes this "transplantation" of explanatory patterns works quite well, but the fundamental problem remains unsolved: What is the nature of the information exchanged between the different levels and how is it transmitted?
Nearly all systems in the world consist of such levels.
And in all cases, there is this shameful lack of knowledge about how the overall system functions.
The group of interdisciplinary scientists who met in Paris loosely formed under the name "Foundations of Information Science".
The researchers come from various countries and fields and have been collaborating on a decentralized basis for eight years.
In addition to scientists from relevant disciplines, art theorists, psychiatrists, language experts, and philosophers are beginning to participate in the discourse.
The majority of the group relies on this "transplantation strategy", in which scientific foundations from one level are adapted and supplemented to another level.
Others, however, consider a completely new approach to be necessary.
In your view, many scientific norms are the product of historical accidents and new ways of thinking are needed.
If the FIS group is lucky, new radical approaches emerge through scientists who currently have no access to the infrastructure of the First World.
Completely free thinking is an underestimated factor.
Almost all activities that take place under the banner of "science" have, like their counterparts in the world of economics, developed an institutional character.
It is believed that developing countries must build up similar resources as industrial countries. This could however suffocate creative thinking.
Many young scientists are currently experiencing a revolution, and many of these – sometimes revolutionary – ideas come from laboratories and research centers that are not connected to the major institutions.
The most sophisticated approaches in the field of mathematical algorithms came for twenty years from the Soviet Union, where there was a lack of computing power everywhere.
The most brilliant and literally world-changing insights in the field of physics over the last decades did not come, as expected, from the well-known innovation centers, but from Budapest.
In Iran, there is a tradition of architecture that contributed to important insights for cognitive scientists.
And the most radical new ideas in the field of second-generation artificial intelligence (the so-called "autonomous agents") come today from Prague.
The most creative scientific achievements entered history.
When Einstein expanded physics with a new way of thinking, it changed the identity of space and time. The FIS conference in July was the unannounced beginning of an attempt to redefine the universe in this way.
Those gaps were identified that require explanations.
More scientists from innovative regions will be added to this group, in order to then identify those problems that could be solved once this new science is developed, or discovered, as one might say.

